tell</h1><!-- Module ends: article-header--></div><div id="mod-article-subtitle" style="" class="mod-articlesubtitle"><!-- Module starts: article-subtitle (ArticleSubtitle) --><h2>Kim Jong Ryul emerges from years of lying low in Austria as he launches a book about his former work procuring luxury items for the ruling Kims as their people suffered. He fears for his life.</h2><!-- Module ends: article-subtitle--></div><!-- Area starts: article-first-block --><div id="area-article-first-block" style=""><div id="mod-article-byline" style="" class="mod-latarticlesarticlebyline mod-articlebyline"><!-- Module starts: article-byline (ArticleByline) --><span class="pubdate"><a href="/2010/apr/04">April 04, 2010</a></span><span class="separator">|</span><span>By Julia Damianova</span><!-- Module ends: article-byline--></div><div id="mod-a-body-first-para" style="" class="mod-latarticlesarticletext mod-articletext"><!-- Module starts: a-body-first-para (ArticleText) --><p>Kim Jong Ryul is a slightly built and lively 75-year-old with large glasses and a gray suit that seems several sizes too big. But Kim wears it anyway. It is virtually his only connection to his past.</p><p> "This is the suit I had on," the North Korean native explains, "when I escaped."</p><p> About 15 years ago, Kim says, he exchanged his upper-echelon North Korean government job for a lonely underground existence in Austria, where he remains in constant fear of assassination.</p><!-- Module ends: a-body-first-para--></div></div><!-- Area ends: article-first-block--><div class="float" style="clear:both;"><img src="/images/pixel.gif" height="1" width="1" alt="" /></div><div id="mod-ctr-lt-in-top" style="" class="mod-adcpc"><!-- Module starts: ctr-lt-in-top (AdCpc) --><script type="text/javascript"> var adSkipCounter = 0; </script>
